{
  "texts": [
    "These derived phoneme-like pseudo labels then serve together with the original targets as hierarchical targets for speech pretraining to learn high-level semantic speech representations, following the principles of HuBERT [2] The contributions of T-HuBERT can be summarized as follows: 1) We first leverage unpaired text information to obtain phonemelike modelling units from speech via unsupervised training, thus eliminating the need of paired data as a bridge for joint pre-training of speech and text [9], [11], [13], [14].2) Compared with the hidden unit of HuBERT, the derived phoneme-like modelling units could effectively guide the pre-trained model to improve its speech representation.",
    "3) Based on previous empirical evidence in [15], we show that the phoneme-like modelling units and the hidden units can jointly guide the pre-trained model to achieve better speech representation.",
    "Given unpaired speech and text data, how does the speech pre-trained model leverage the additional unpaired text to benefit the downstream speech-related tasks?",
    "As speech and text are two different forms of a language, they are inherently similar in terms of phonetic, phonotactic, and lexical distribution.",
    "The question is how we draw an equivalence between the self-organized phonetic units, i.e."
  ]
